Updated Definition

  • Def [Version 2.0]: A strategy is said to be Never a Best Response provided that it is never a component of a playerâs best response function â taking into account mixed strategies

    • In other words, a strategy is an NBR provided that it isnât in the upper envelope of an agentâs expected payoff graph

  • For the updated definition, I will also use NBR interchangeably with non-rationalizable

    • We could say an agentâs strategy is rationalizable if it is in ever a component of the agentâs best response function

NBR Example

  • The game:

  • We have seen this game before. Recall:

    • \(BR_1(X)=F\)
    • \(BR_1(Y)=G\)

  • It is tempting to want to say that \(H\) is Never a Best Response, because player 1 would always rather play something other than \(H\) in response to a pure strategy

    • Should player 1 ever play \(H\)?

NBR Example â player 1

  • Suppose player 2 is playing \(\tau=qX+(1-q)Y\)
  • Game
  • E.P. Graph
  • Upper Envelope
  • BR function

\[BR_1(q)= \begin{cases} G & q < q_1^*\\ {G, H} & q = q_1^*\\ H & q_1^*\le q \le q_2^*\\ {H, F} & q = q_2^*\\ F & q>q_2^* \end{cases} \]

What about player 2?

  • Note: intersection points in the upper envelope of an expected payoff graph reveal candidates for MSNE

    • But not every intersection in the upper envelope is guaranteed to be a MSNE

  • To see this, consider the previous example

    • We know player 1 will never play a totally mixed strategy: if they were to mix, theyâd mix between \(G\) and \(H\) or \(F\) and \(H\)

    • Letâs look at player 2âs expected payoff graphs for each of the following mixed strategies player 1 may rationally play

      • \(\sigma_1=pG+(1-p)H\)

      • \(\sigma_2=rF+(1-r)H\)

Player 2âs E.P. graphs

  • Assume player 1 is playing \(\sigma_1=pG+(1-p)H\)
  • Game
  • E.P. Graph
  • BR function

\[BR_2(\sigma_1(p))= \begin{cases} Y & p < p^*\\ {X, Y} & p = p^*\\ X & p>p^* \end{cases} \]

Player 2âs E.P. graphs (cont.)

  • Assume player 1 is playing \(\sigma_2=rF+(1-r)H\)
  • Game
  • E.P. Graph
  • BR function
  • Notes
  • Reasoning

\[BR_2(\sigma_2(r))= \begin{cases} Y & r \in [0,1] \end{cases} \]

  • If player 1 is playing \(\sigma_2=rF+(1-r)H\), then player 2 should always play \(Y\)

  • We know there is no PSNE, so this will lead to a loop of best responses which does not converge to a NE (see âReasoningâ{.alert2} for details)

  • Therefore, there is no MSNE where player 1 plays \(\sigma_2\)

  • If player 1 is playing \(\sigma_2=rF+(1-r)H\), then player 2 should always play \(Y\)

    • If player 2 is playing \(Y\), player 1 should play \(G\)

    • \(\implies\) player 2 should play \(X\)

    • \(\implies\) player 1 should play \(F\)

    • \(\implies\) player 2 should play \(Y\)

    • \(\implies\) â¦

MSNE in 3x2 Example

  • Soâ¦ we know we are looking for a single MSNE when player 1 is playing \(\sigma_1\) (which I will now call \(\sigma\)) and player 2 is playing \(\tau\)
  • Game (tau)
  • Step 1.0
  • Step 1.1
  • Game (sigma)
  • Step 2.0
  • Step 2.1
  • MSNE

  • Assume player 2 is playing \(\tau=qX+(1-q)Y\)

  • Then, player 1 gets

    • \(u_1(G)=5q+6(1-q)\)

    • \(u_1(H)=6q+5(1-q)\)

  • Player 1 will mix between \(G\) and \(H\) when they are indifferent between these payoffs

\[ \begin{align*} 5q+6(1-q) & = 6q+5(1-q) \\ \implies q^* =q_1^* &= \frac{1}{2} \end{align*} \]

  • Remark: to be careful, we may also want to verify that \(u_1(G)\)\(^\dagger\) yields a greater payoff \(u_1(F)\) when \(p=1/2\), but I wonât ask you to do this

    • \(\dagger\) : Or \(u_1(H)\). Or \(u_1(\sigma_1)\). They are all equal by construction.

  • Assume player 1 is playing \(\sigma=pG+(1-p)H\)

  • Then, player 1 gets

    • \(u_2(X)=2p+(1-p)=1+p\)

    • \(u_2(Y)=p+4(1-p)=4-3p\)

  • Player 2 will mix between \(X\) and \(Y\) when they are indifferent between these payoffs

\[ \begin{align*} 1+p & = 4-3p \\ 4p &= 3\\ \implies p^* &= \frac{3}{4} \end{align*} \]

Therefore, our MSNE is

\[ \left\{\frac{3}{4}G+\frac{1}{4}H, \frac{1}{2}X+\frac{1}{2}Y\right\}\\ \] or \[\{\sigma_1(3/4), \tau(1/2)\}\] or \[((F,G,H); (X,Y)) \rightarrow \left\{\left(0,\frac{3}{4}, \frac{1}{4}\right); \left(\frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{2}\right)\right\}\]

  • This is not what I want to focus on

  • From the expected payoff graphs â namely, from the upper envelopes â we found the following BR functions for each player: \[ BR_1(\tau(q))= \begin{cases} F & q<0.25\\ \{R,F\} & q=0.25\\ R & q>0.25 \end{cases}% \hspace{2em} BR_2(\sigma(p))= \begin{cases} F & p<0.75\\ \{R,F\} & p=0.75\\ R & q>0.75 \end{cases}% \]

  • Recall that we assume player 1 is playing \(\sigma(p)=pR+(1-p)F\) and player 2 is playing \(\tau(q)=qR+(1-q)F\)

  • Idea: letâs rewrite the BR functions as written above in terms of each playerâs own strategy

    • Put another way: convert the BR functions to be in terms of the probability parameters

Converting BR functions

  • We assume player 1 is playing \(\sigma(p)=pR+(1-p)F\) and player 2 is playing \(\tau(q)=qR+(1-q)F\) \[ BR_1(\tau(q))= \begin{cases} F & q<0.25\\ \{R,F\} & q=0.25\\ R & q>0.25 \end{cases}% \hspace{2em} BR_2(\sigma(p))= \begin{cases} F & p<0.75\\ \{R,F\} & p=0.75\\ R & q>0.75 \end{cases}% \]
  • Idea
  • Example
  • Conversion

  • Letâs rewrite the BR functions as written above in terms of each playerâs own strategy

  • Put another way: convert the BR functions to be in terms of the probability parameters

  • Player 1 playing \(F\) means playing \(\sigma(0)=0R+(1-0)F\), so \(F\) corresponds to \(p=0\) for player 1

  • Player 1 playing \(R\) means playing \(\sigma(1)=1R+(1-1)F\), so \(R\) corresponds to \(p=1\) for player 1

  • \(\{R,F\}\) means player 1 is indifferent between \(R\) and \(F\) â and everything in between â so this corresponds to \(p\in[0,1]\)

  • For this game specifically, these correspondences are symmetric for player 2

  • Using the strategy definitions, our BR functions can be converted into the following

    \[ p^{BR}(\tau(q)) = \begin{cases} 0 & q<0.25\\ [0,1] & q=0.25\\ 1 & q>0.25 \end{cases}% \hspace{2em} q^{BR}(\sigma(p))= \begin{cases} 0 & p<0.75\\ [0,1] & p=0.75\\ 1 & q>0.75 \end{cases}% \]

Best Response Graph

  • Now, we have numeric BR functions

    \[ p^{BR}(\tau(q)) = \begin{cases} 0 & q<0.25\\ [0,1] & q=0.25\\ 1 & q>0.25 \end{cases}% \hspace{2em} q^{BR}(\sigma(p))= \begin{cases} 0 & p<0.75\\ [0,1] & p=0.75\\ 1 & q>0.75 \end{cases}% \]

  • Letâs plot them in \(pq\)-space

Player 1

\[ p^{BR}(\tau(q)) = \begin{cases} 0 & q<0.25\\ [0,1] & q=0.25\\ 1 & q>0.25 \end{cases}% \]

  • How to read:
    • âWhen \(q\) lives in \([0, 0.25]\), \(p=0\)â
    • âWhen \(q\) lives in \([0.25, 1]\), \(p=1\)â
    • âWhen \(q\) exactly equals \(0.25\), \(p\) can take on any value in \([0,1]\)â

Player 2

\[ q^{BR}(\sigma(p))= \begin{cases} 0 & p<0.75\\ [0,1] & p=0.75\\ 1 & q>0.75 \end{cases} \]

  • How to read:
    • âWhen \(p\) lives in \([0, 0.75]\), \(q=0\)â
    • âWhen \(p\) lives in \([0.75, 1]\), \(q=1\)â
    • âWhen \(p\) exactly equals \(0.75\), \(q\) can take on any value in \([0,1]\)â
